ecommended Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile many researchers study offenders and offending, few actually journey into the correctional world to meet offenders face to face. This book offers researchers, practitioners, and students a step-by-step guide to effectively research correctional populations, providing field-tested advice for those studying youth and adults on probation, on parole, and in jails and prisons. The book addresses topics such as how to build rapport with offenders and those who monitor them; how to select from the many types of correctional data that can be collected; how to navigate the informed consent process and maintain research ethics; and how to manage the logistics of doing research. With personal stories, “what if” scenarios, case studies, and real-world tools like checklists and sample forms, the authors share methods of negotiating the complexities that researchers often face as they work with those behind bars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCorrectional institutionszUnited StatesxData processing. 0aCorrectionsxResearchzUnited States. 0aCriminal statisticszUnited States. 0aCriminologyxResearchzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  abehind bars.  acase studies.  achecklist.  aconvicts.  acops.  acorrectional facilities.  acorrections officer.  acrime and punishment.  acriminal justice.  acriminals.  adetention centers.  afield research.  ahealing.  ajail.  ajuvenile detention.  aoffenders.  aoffending.  aofficers.  aparole.  apersonal stories.  apolice work.  apolice.  apractitioners.  aprison.  aprisoners.  aprobation.  areal world.  arecovery.  awhat if.1 aLane, Jodi, eauthor.4aut4http